latestPosts.caption:
Located on the banks of the Betwa River, Orchha has an old world charm. 
There are a lot of interesting places to visit in Orchha, especially for history enthusiasts. Even if you are not into history, the magnificence of the place will definitely draw you in! 

A quick travel guide....save for later 🤗

The nearest major railway station  is  Jhansi, around 20 km away.
If you are flying in, the nearest airport is Gwalior Airport, 130 km away. 

Getting around in Orchha 
It is a fairly small place & you can easily walk to most of the attractions. Alternately, you can hire E rikshaws, which are easily available. 

The entire town is within a radius of 5 km and you can easily plan your trip in 2 days. 
You can definitely jump from one monument to the other, do the touristy thing of taking insta-worthy photographs 😄, but the best way to explore Orchha is to savour the place. 

Amazing places to visit in Orchha 

1. Orchha fort complex: 
This architectural marvel dominates the skyline of this town containing palaces, gardens, gateways, pavillions & Sheesh mahal, which is now a hotel.

2.Chaturbhuj temple:
It is one of the tallest  Hindu temples. A temple recognising Vishnu and Rama, Chaturbhuj is located close to the Orchha Fort. Morning visits are from 8 am – 12:30 pm and evening visits are between the hours of 5pm and 10pm.

3. Ram Raja temple:
This temple is unique as it is the only temple in all of India where Lord Rama is worshipped as a King.

4. Situated on the banks of Betwa river, Chattris is a set of magnificent royal tombs of the Maharajas, placed on a platform and supported by the pillars. The charm of Chattris is best experienced when it is viewed from a narrow bridge on the opposite side of the river.

5. Nature trail: 
This 12km long nature trail in the Orchha Natural Reserve can be a beautifully enriching experience. Its also a good place to just cycle around.

6. Rafting :
The adventurous side of the city begins when you start seeing rafts on the river Betwa. Experience the amazing rapids & beautiful sight of the city from a different angle!

latestPosts.caption:
Gauhar Mahal 
More than 200 years old it was built by the first woman ruler of Bhopal, Qudsia Begum , who was nicknamed ‘Gauhar'
The palace, which was residential as well as a working place for the Begum, is known for its Indo-Islamic architecture.
One feels both sad and happy when you see this place. It's a magnificent palace with many doors, hallways etc and a brilliant view of the lake.
The palace is presently in ruins and needs a lot of restoration work before it comes on the main tourist circuit of Bhopal. 
Upon leaving the Gohar Mahal, cross the busy main road to the side of the Upper Lake and head west away from the city center. A short distance along here is a statue of Raja Bhoj, king of the Parmar dynasty. This is a new landmark in the city, having been unveiled in 2011.

Timings: 8 AM - 6 PM

Entry: Free

latestPosts.caption:
Maladevi temple, Gyaraspur 

An experience beyond words ..... Wonder why we keep epitomising the very few monuments that everyone knows and miss out such precious jewels!
 Mala Devi temple is unique and comes under the rare category of partial rock-cut and partial structural temples. 
This is a 9 th century Hindu/Jain temple overlooking a beautiful Valley.
The intricate carvings will mesmerize &  remind you  of the glory that India once was.
A must see! Highly recommended ..... your vehicle can go right up-to the temple ...... Just a km detour from the highway.

How to reach :
Gyaraspur is situated on NH146, connecting Bhopal to Sagar.
Entry fee : Free 
Timings : Sunrise to Sunset (It's an ASI protected monument)
Tips : Winter/light monsoon would be ideal time to visit. It can get very hot in summer, so early morning would be preferable.
